column24: The Internet, a worldwide organization, is an amazingly intricate specialized framework based on the innovative commitments of researchers around the globe from the 1950s to the present 2020. All through its advancement, the challenges that my Superhero Internet will face: 1. Digital Divide: The digital divide, as a whole, remains an enormous and complicated issue heavily interwoven with the issues of unequal access in terms of education, income and race. The obstacle, however, is by no means insurmountable if broken down into specific tasks that must be upcoming challenges. a. Unequal Access: We live in a less equal country than at any point since the Gilded Age. This gaping inequality may not be the fault of the Internet, but this will be the upcoming biggest challenges of my superhero internet. b. Education: Widening levels of education will magnify the digital divide. Households with higher levels of education are increasingly more likely to use computers and the Internet. It has been observed that those with college degrees or higher are 10 times more likely to have internet access at work as than those with only a high school education. c. Income: Not surprisingly, and in direct correlation to education, the levels of household income will also play a significant role in the widening gap. d. Race: At the same time, the digital divide continues to widen along very specific racial lines. 2. Cyber Security: The risk and severity of cyber-attacks have clearly grown over the past few years. In fact, this will become a threat related to massive data breaches, flaws in microchips, cryptojacking, and many others. 3. Slow Internet Speed: During the COVID-19 school building closures, big equity problems around internet access emerged. Most of the developing countries have access to the Internet, but only at slow speeds.

column24: My Superhero is a doctor and he is caring for seriously ill patients often face difficult decisions about appropriate care for his patients. These decisions can be emotionally laden under the best of circumstances, and become even more challenging under highly stressful circumstances such as the Covid-19 pandemic for instance. With Covid-19, the numbers of patients UN agency desperately want care, few effective treatments, high risks for sickness transmission, and inadequacy of essential resources will cause ethical distress. My superhero is facing several problems. He is facing shortages of PPE including face masks, gowns, and respirators. There's not been a lot of rest with COVID-19 because when my hero comes home, he has to worry that his family could get sick. He is doing long duty hours, which is a major risk factor for him to acquire infection. But he is getting violence from some irresponsible public in the hospital. He could be dying due to Covid-19. The hospital is getting overloaded, essential medical equipment scarce. He can spread the infection to colleagues, family members, friends, and patients. He knows that treating Covid-19 patients means he can also be putting his own family at risk. Going home at the end of a shift doesn't mean he can leave worry about the disease behind. The risk to personal health from the coronavirus is alarming enough, but the risk of infecting his family because of exposure on the job is unjustified and not acceptable. We sent Covid-19 affected people to the hospital and he is only the person who treatment and stays with them. So he risks his life, fighting the Covid-19 crisis with worldwide lockdown, he is working day and night to minimize the damage due to the pandemic with constant checks on the patients, either through phone/video conferencing.

column24: The main character, Fikri, faces a myriad of challenges after realizing that the Pralaya, the primordial antagonist which plays on humanity's greed, has overpowered the good in humanity. As humans get further influenced by Pralaya, the ancient deity becomes stronger and in consequence harms the Earth. Scientists estimate we're now losing species at 1,000 to 10,000 times the "background" rate, with dozens going extinct every day. As many as 30 to 50 percent of all species are possibly heading toward extinction by mid-century. 99% of currently threatened species are at risk from human activities, primarily those driving habitat loss, the introduction of exotic species, and global warming. The human's greediness is also visualized by shocking statistics on our trash tendencies. The data shows that humans throw away 7.2 million tonnes of food every year whilst half of it still edible. Meanwhile, 1 in 7 people across the world don't have enough to eat. Most of this plastic ends up in the ocean. By 2050, the ocean will contain more plastic by weight than fish. This waste causes greenhouse gas emissions. Biodegradable items in landfills rot and decompose will produce methane, which contributes to global warming. Fikri grew up amidst this downfall of Earth due to the infection of greed that has corrupted humanity, but he managed to find hope amongst this darkness. Ever since Fikri stumbled upon an ancient scripture and an unplanned interaction with a cat, he felt the pull to bring back the hope of humanity. Through his journey, he encounters overly zealous politicians that sympathize more with profit than endangered species. Coincidentally, the Komodo Dragon, holds the answers to the secrets of the ancients. Amidst this chaos, the Komodo Dragon unleashes the suffering it and many of the marine lives have to endure due to humanity's selfishness.

column24: My hero (name: Niall) is a soldier in a civil war. He didn't know much about war until he was sent to the front lines. He started to doubt what he is doing is right or not. Eventually, he decided that there was no point in fighting and deserts from the army. During his escape from the army, he found a decent hiding spot - a cave with a tiny entrance. He went inside and saw a little statue of a goddess  it seems to be the 'goddess of protection' from a mythical culture. In front of the statue is a piece of crystal-like stone, with a hole drilled, allowing it to be hanged as a pendant. According to myths, it seems to harbour the power of a protective barrier. Using plants he picked up during his escape, he extracted the fibres and twinned it into a string. He took the stone and used the string to hang it around his neck as a lucky charm. After he left the cave, he encountered an explosion. This is when the power of the pendant awakens  it forms a force field around the holder and blocked the impact. Noticing what the pendant can do, Niall decides that he shall travel among the front lines, and utilize his powers in protecting people who are affected by war. There will be some challenges that Niall would face  how will he use his newly discovered power? How can he help people (i.e. mentally: delivering hope to people in desperate situations, and physically: protecting them from hazards)? And the biggest question  How can he change the current situation? Niall will have to decide what his final goals are, and built up his resolve as it will not be an easy journey.

column24: The challenges that Angel X faces in her mission are of poverty , gender inequality and access to contaminated water. column24: Child labour is a systemic problem around the world that keeps successive generations in poverty. Anya, our superhero comes across such a case of hazardous child labour and has to defeat the contractors practicing it and also provide feasible solutions to the parents and children caught in the vicious, helpless circle of poverty. After being informed by her friend Viren about the children excavating mica in the mines, Sudiksha's first challenge is fighting off the four goons sent by the contractors. The goons get into an argument with Viren and his two coworkers at the site. The chief goon pulls out a gun from nowhere, causing panic. Sudiksha arrives as Anya and takes on the goons. Through her staff, she releases her kokoro power and knocks three of them senseless. Her telepathy is not at the stage and speed that she can dodge bullets. She tells the fourth goon to drive off with his friends. However, the families in the village get scared by the news of this attack. They have not seen Anya yet. They inform the social workers that mining indeed is the only economic activity in the area. It is the question of survival  the children's as well. It is a huge setback for the team. Rapid disappearance of a number of species is considered as one of earth's environmental worries which is more serious problem than pollution global warming and depletion of ozone layer. Factors that cause extinction of species Habitat loss Habitat loss is the process by which natural habitat is damaged or destroyed to such an extent that it is no longer capable of supporting species and ecological communities which naturally occur there. Habitat loss in the terrestrial ecosystem is because of teh following factors. Human Activities Habitat loss maybe directly by human activities which involve clearing of the forest land and indirectly by certain activities which are responsible for air and water pollution climate change and also poaching of animals . Natural factors Habitat loss occurs due to natural factors such as earthquake volcanic eruptions flood etc Rapid growth in population. Habitat loss is increasing day by day with rapidly growing human population Protection of Habitat To protect habitat of many plants and animals government bodies at local national and international level need to emphasize the following. In addition, labour is required for daily operation, maintenance of the digesters, supervision, feeding, storage and disposal of slurry. The The daily biogas needs increase with family size and consequently the cost will also increase certainly. 2 The following biogas substrates are found in the rural areas; cow dung, goat dung, sheep dung and donkey dung. The quantity of substrate entering the digesters should be consistent for long term operations. Biogas digesters are installed on the assumption that there is a consistent supply of substrate daily or weekly. 3 Education is one of greatest challenges hampering the progress of biogas technology in Nigeria. To have a viable and sustainable biogas system, it is important to educate the community on economic, social, health and environmental merits of biogas technology. 4 Inadequate expertise for construction and maintenance of biogas digesters is another constraint that will hinder the dissemination of biogas technology. As our world grows more divisive, the Negotiator will need to step in before the flames start spreading. She'll face a variety of situations: working with politicians to reach an agreement between two opposing parties, working with world leaders where she will end wars and initiate treaties, resolving altercations, and even resolving issues on the internet such as cyberbullying. However, the Negotiator will have to face the challenge of securing a compromise between the two parties. After all, the world isn't black or white. There's no clear "good" or "evil". For example, two politicians may argue whether or not fracking should be banned. One politician may argue that fracking increases the amount of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere, contributing to global climate change. On the other hand, another politician may argue that banning fracking will take away jobs from people in the oil industry, thus harming the economy and individuals alike. Both sides present a strong argument so it's difficult to discern which one is exactly right. We want to protect our planet but we also want to protect our economy. So how will the Negotiator tackle this issue? First, the Negotiator will try to calm both parties down. Next, using her Supercomputer made from an unknown metal, the Negotiator will conduct research. She'll research the arguments made from both opposing parties, drawing evidence from academic journals, experiments, etc. Using this research, the Negotiator will use her super-intelligence to formulate a plan on how to combine the proposals of the two opposing sides. Ultimately, the Negotiator's plan will reap the benefits of the proposals from both sides without any of the drawbacks. If that is not probable, the Negotiator will analyze which side would have the least drawbacks and present that argument to the two opposing parties.

Human conflicts in our society are driven by hatred and a lack of compassion or sympathy. Criminals don't stop and think about who their selfish actions are hurting. Murderers don't stop and think about their victims' loved ones, or even the victim's own fear. Corrupt police officers don't stop and think about the fear the person in front of them has when they realize they may be prosecuted or killed for something they didn't do. Politicians that vote against human rights don't think about the effects their vote has on the people who will be losing their rights, whether that is the right to love, the right to be comfortable in your own skin, the ability to have control over your own body, etc. Most of the time, these people aren't anywhere close to the category of people being affected. Bigots don't stop and think about the effects that their words or actions have on the people they're oppressing. They see those who are different from them as subhuman, or the enemy--regardless, someone who couldn't or shouldn't feel the same way others typically do. Karma's job is to put a stop to hatred in our society by making the oppressors realize that these are *other people* they are hurting, that these people have emotions and thoughts just like them. She uses her Empath ability to make them realize the hurt they are causing by reversing the pain back on them.

Agent Welfare spends her days battling the Global Water Crisis, also known as her archenemy GWC. GWC is a small gnome-like creature whose size makes him hard to catch. He constantly creates challenges for Agent Welfare by contaminating rivers, lakes, and oceans. Whether it is through polluting the water with trash or spilling in harmful chemicals, GWC is always creating new ways to make it harder for Agent Welfare to take care of the world's bodies of water. He also builds obstacles, such as mountains and droughts, that make it harder for populations around the world to gain easy access to water. The harsh and unpredictable climate and weather he creates not only makes it harder for Agent Welfare to maintain wells and other infrastructures, but also increases chances of illnesses that weaken populations. Such challenges pose as a barrier to the welfare of a population, as they spend most of their time trying to find water or are too weak to work. However, Agent Welfare does not let this discourage her. Her special watch notifies her of any reportings of contaminated water, so she can quickly filter any pollutants or chemicals. She also maps out and builds infrastructures that allow for easier access to water, such as pumps, wells, and plumbing systems. With the help of the top scientists and architects around the world, she constantly seeks to find new materials and structures that could withstand the challenges created by GWC.

Gaea's real name is Himari and she was originally from Japan until she lost her family during the Fukushima Nuclear Blast in 2011 and had to move to San Francisco to live with her uncle and his family where she discovers her new powers. Gaea is the hope that worlds needs in order to get motivated to prevent climate change because she can actually create long lasting affects as long as they are willing to put in the effort to create a more sustainable society. In this comic, Gaea encourages the masses to help prevent The Trump Administration from trying to sell oil leases in Arctic Refuges. By utilizing social media she is able to get enough people's attention that global organizations are able to then use legal methods to precent the oil drilling and continue to lead a more sustainable society with Gaea at the head. Her powers will only help everyone, if they do their part to help reduce greenhouse gas emissions.

Mental health issues are on the rise and as the world around us becomes more unstable and chaotic, the stress is causing many people's mental health to deteriorate. People of all ages are experiencing many anxiety inducing events recently, including experiencing financial or medical hardships, having to adapt to an online world, dealing with a limited or lack of access to friends and family, and losing jobs or even loved ones. Unfortunately today, especially with so many people losing their jobs and experiencing financial instability due to Covid-19, many people suffering from anxiety related mental illnesses are not able to receive the treatment that they desire and need. This has made it even harder than it would normally be for people to access help. Sammy the Anxiety Soother aims to solve this problem, and today's climate has made her job increasingly more important. Sammy responds to multiple people a day, she can sense with her super powers when someone nearby is experiencing unhealthy levels of anxiety. Her job is to first sooth them using her magic calming powers, then she evaluates their mental state, with the help of her PhD in psychology, and offers the person her help. Many people's issue with lack of treatment access comes from their financial situation, stigmas, and many other factors. No matter the reason, Sammy aims to break down these barriers for people, whether it be educating someone on why treatment is important and helpful, finding them a therapist or medication, or even paying for their treatment; Sammy does whatever she can to help. While she is up against an increasing number of challenges, with her powers, knowledge, and wealth, she will continue to work tirelessly to aid everyone's mental health that she can.

column24: Our Superhero will encounter the problem of xenophobia especially revolving around refugees throughout the world. Xenophobia is the hatred and fear of foreigners that can be met with hostility toward these individuals. This issue places a large obstacle for people that immigrated to countries as it causes them to have decreased economic and social opportunities due to the implicit bias that they face. Acts of discrimination, hate crimes, as well as foreign policies are examples that show the effects of xenophobia on a society and these individuals. As refugees flee their home countries due to social, political, economic, and religious reasons, their journey towards a better life is a difficult one. Even after they are able to safely reach a country to stay, many refugees have to overcome more challenges associated with xenophobia and discrimination in order to create a good foundation for their future. Refugees such as those from Middle Eastern descent in Europe seek jobs that regular citizens could get and are judges solely based on their ethnic background. This destabilizes their economic equal rights as well as educational opportunities. Muslim immigrants are faced with challenges regarding assimilation and entering the country of Poland, due to xenophobic remarks and policies created by their leaders. In addition, Latinx refugees going into the United States are faced with many challenges and are placed in migrant detention camps with limited amounts of access to healthcare, education, and many basic human rights are infringed in these overcrowded facilities. Our superhero Rashida Ortiz can help combat these issues through her ability of telepathy. She can help spread information, educate people, to promote the understanding and acceptance of refugees worldwide.

column24: Earthanator will face a complex set of challenges in pursuit of reforestation. Replanting forests is not as simple as placing more trees wherever space exists. Earthanator will first have to obtain the land and then make it suitable for trees to grow. Earthanator is a robot, so it has been equipped with a diplomacy module to procure land from farmers and corporations. Earthanator uses a combination of funds to bargain for land and deforestation data to teach farmers their practices' harmful effects. Reforestation will inevitably hurt individuals' livelihoods in the short term. However, Earthanator's diplomacy module allows it to feel empathy for the affected, and Earthanator's unrivaled processing power enables it to devise the best possible compromise between corporation and forest health. After obtaining land, Earthanator faces a second challenge: revitalizing the soil. Farming of monocultures exhausts the soil of nutrients, and the use of pesticides and herbicides alters soil's microbial ecosystem. To solve these issues, Earthanator's multifaceted scanning system takes assays of soil samples. After consolidating the data, Earthanator determines the correct chemicals to use to restore soil fertility and speed up sapling growth. Finally, the third challenge: Earthanator must work to reverse ecological damages caused by deforestation beyond those restricted to within the farm plot. Mass felling and burning of trees severely deplete ecosystem biodiversity. Secondly, soil erosion due to lack of tree roots pollutes aquatic ecosystems with sediment. Watersheds are also impacted by agrochemical runoff, which gives ecosystems an overload of nutrients as well as harmful pesticides. To solve these issues, Earthanator will use thermal detection and recording technology to quickly and efficiently record species population data. Earthanator will then send this data to scientists with the goal of stabilizing these ecosystems before it's too late to save them.

It's an unknown, but we do know that as temperatures rise, crop productivity declines. Climate-induced changes will affect food prices, a critical consideration for the world's poor. Biological impacts on crop yields work through the economic system resulting in reduced production, higher crop and meat prices, and a reduction in cereal consumption. This reduction means reduced calorie intake and increased childhood malnutrition .People in low-income countries face the impact of climate change on a daily basiseven though they contribute least to greenhouse gas emissions. Erratic and more severe weather patterns affect their livelihoods and food security. The effects of climate change are becoming more noticeable in wealthier parts of the world, but poor and marginalized communities, especially women and indigenous populations, in low-income countries are even more vulnerable than before to shocks beyond their control.

column24: When I talked with Hazel Holmes during an interview last week, she was positively glowing. I later asked her where this new exuberance had come from. "I'm living my dream," she told me. When I asked if she could elaborate, she told me, "As a little girl, I knew I wanted to stay connected with the ocean for the rest of my life. "When I start my day in the time of Covid-19, I like to go for a run or walk at my local beach," she replied. "This gets me energized and ready for my day. Sometimes I will bring a bag with me to gather garbage in, but now that the beaches have been extremely quiet, I find myself doing it less often. Almost all of my free time is spent volunteering at my local turtle rescue hospital, or chatting with other wildlife activists like myself through social media. Most of my other time is spent taking care of schoolwork and tuning into class on my laptop." "That's amazing," I said. "Throughout everything you have done in your community, and moving on in the future, what has been and what do you think will be your greatest challenge or challenges?" column24: Dear Diary, Yesterday I felt hopeless. I once again was disappointed by someone's intolerance and hasty judgment. But my belief that one day we will wake up in a society that accepts, respects, and values other people's uniqueness has never faded. While strolling through the park, my attention was caught by unpleasant noise. Surrounded by a group of people, a boy was sitting on a bench. He hanged his head down and was nervous. But others were only concerned about why he did not reply to the question of a nearby passing man. The man felt aggrieved by the boy's disregard yet had no idea about his medical condition. I felt that the boy wanted to say something but couldn't. I rushed to him to stop the mockery. When I looked into the boy's scared eyes, he seemed to be asking for help. Suddenly I heard his voice, but his lips were not moving. I could feel his pain, concerns, and thoughts. It turned out the silent boy suffers from selective mutism - a disorder when a child is unable to speak and communicate in select social settings. Feeling ashamed of other's behavior, I stood up and explained why he could not talk. That's why, dear Diary, we should never judge a book by its cover! I hope the people I encountered in the park also learned a life-long lesson. By the way, you know what? Today I also helped a girl by hearing her inner voice and feeling her emotions. I think I discovered my superpower, and I believe God blessed me because I have a will to fight inequality and the exclusive society challenges. Despite the absence of my forearm, I can empathize with people in need and make their voices count thanks to this gift. ~ Amelia

In fact, the number of storms have been increasing annually due to the effects of global warming, which threatens millions of homes and futures. Lastly, Captain Green encounters a problem that is a turning point in this comic: the residents of Earth themselves! As proved by years of scientific evidence, the human population has how oceans with tons of trash, killed animals, and added toxins into the atmosphere. This shows that although we can implement laws to combat global warming, our individual actions are also the most impactful. column24: The Challenges are: CO2 is a global pollutant that can't be locally contained The first key feature of climate change that puts it at odds with past environmental issues is that it's a global pollutant, rather than a local pollutant. Power plants and other industry installations are the main CO2 emitters. The current global average temperature is 0.85ºC higher than it was in the late 19th century. For now, climate change is still hypothetical The damage caused by most climate change pollutants will happen in the future. Which means most of us won't truly be affected by climate change  it's a hypothetical scenario conveyed in charts and graphs. There's no direct link to a smoking gun Despite the global threat from climate-altering pollutants, it's hard for scientists to link them to a specific environmental disaster. Without a definitive culprit, it's easier for skeptics to ignore or explain away climate change effects. Modern living is part of the problem It's a tough pill to swallow, but modern conveniences like electricity, transportation, and air conditioning contribute to climate change, and remedies potentially involve significant sacrifice and lifestyle change. Many of these gases occur naturally, but human activity is increasing the concentrations of some of them in the atmosphere, in particular: Burning coal, oil and gas produces CO2 and NO, deforestation, increasing livestock farming, fertilisers containing nitrogen, fluorinated gases produce a very strong warming effect. Developing countries contribute to a large share of pollution Simply put, this isn't their top priority. While asking very poor countries that are worried about where their next meal is coming from, or whether they can send their kids to school, to incur costs to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to benefit the world. And that's a tough ask for a policymaker inside of a developing country.
